ny state in the union. African Americans called on these institutions to build a statewide movement to regain the right to vote after World War I. African American women played a decisive role in the campaign as they mobilized in the months leading up to the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment. The 1920 contest culminated in the bloodiest Election Day in modern American history, when white supremacists and the Ku Klux Klan violently, and with state sanction, prevented African Americans from voting. Ortiz's eloquent interpretation of the many ways that black Floridians fought to expand the meaning of freedom beyond formal equality and his broader consideration of how people resist oppression and create new social movements illuminate a strategic era of United States history and reveal how the legacy of legal segregation continues to play itself out to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryxFlorida. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszFloridaxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmentx19th centuryxFlorida. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmentx20th centuryxFlorida. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsxFlorida. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxSocial conditions. 0aRacismxHistoryx19th centuryxFlorida. 0aRacismxHistoryx20th centuryxFlorida. 0aRacismzFloridaxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismzFloridaxHistoryy20th century. 0aViolencexHistoryx19th centuryxFlorida. 0aViolencexHistoryx20th centuryxFlorida. 0aViolencezFloridaxHistoryy19th century. 0aViolencezFloridaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a19th amendment.  a19th century american 